<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1418,2021]" pageId="1" pageNumber="435">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1418,1445]" pageId="1" pageNumber="435">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new species is superficially similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Holloway, 1987" authorityName="Holloway" authorityYear="1987" box="[749,1107,1418,1445]" class="Insecta" family="Limacodidae" genus="Parasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="435" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="semperi">
<emphasis box="[749,924,1419,1444]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="435">Parasa semperi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Holloway, J. D. &amp; Cock, M. J. W. &amp; Desmier de Chenon, R." box="[930,1107,1418,1445]" pageId="1" pageNumber="435" pagination="15 - 117" refId="ref2626" refString="Holloway, J. D., Cock, M. J. W. &amp; Desmier de Chenon, R. (1987) Systematic account of South-east Asian pest Limacodidae. In: Cock, M. J. W., Godfray, H. C. J. &amp; Holloway, J. D. (Eds.), Slug and Nettle Caterpillars: The biology, taxonomy and control of the Limacodidae of economic importance on palms in South-East Asia. Cab International, Wallingford, pp. 15 - 117." type="book chapter" year="1987">Holloway, 1987</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1121,1199,1418,1445]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1279,1304]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,301,1260]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,301,1260]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Adults.1. Polyphena herbifera, Nepal (in MWM).2. P. bana, China Guangdong (in SCAU). 3. P.chongzuoensis sp. nov., holotype. 4. Parasa semperi, holotype (in NHM). Scale bar =10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3385535/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="435">Figs. 4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1210,1225,1419,1445]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1919,1944]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,191,1879]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,174,1879]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–10. Male genitalia. 5. Polyphena herbifera, Nepal (genital slide 11211, in MWM). 6. P. bana, China, Guangdong (in SCAU). 7. P. chongzuoensis sp. nov., holotype. 8. Parasa semperi, Philippines, Luzon (genital slide 20018, in MWM). 9. Juxta and anellus of Polyphena chongzuoensis sp. nov., holotype. 10. Tip of aedeagus of P. chongzuoensis sp. nov., holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3385537/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="435">8</figureCitation>
), but can be distinguished from the latter by the basal area of hindwing reddish brown, green patch of forewings with fuzzy margins, anellus in male genitalia has two rows of spines. 
<taxonomicName authority="Li &amp; Solovyev &amp; Wang, 2019" authorityName="Li &amp; Solovyev &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2019" box="[701,991,1490,1516]" class="Insecta" family="Limacodidae" genus="Polyphena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="435" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chongzuoensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[701,991,1490,1516]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="435">Polyphena chongzuoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[999,1088,1491,1517]" pageId="1" pageNumber="435">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[999,1088,1491,1517]" pageId="1" pageNumber="435" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cai" baseAuthorityYear="1983" box="[1143,1226,1490,1516]" class="Insecta" family="Limacodidae" genus="Polyphena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="435" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bana">
<emphasis box="[1143,1226,1490,1516]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="435">P. bana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1242,1321,1490,1517]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1279,1304]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,301,1260]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,301,1260]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Adults.1. Polyphena herbifera, Nepal (in MWM).2. P. bana, China Guangdong (in SCAU). 3. P.chongzuoensis sp. nov., holotype. 4. Parasa semperi, holotype (in NHM). Scale bar =10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3385535/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="435">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1333,1348,1490,1517]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1919,1944]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,191,1879]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,174,1879]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–10. Male genitalia. 5. Polyphena herbifera, Nepal (genital slide 11211, in MWM). 6. P. bana, China, Guangdong (in SCAU). 7. P. chongzuoensis sp. nov., holotype. 8. Parasa semperi, Philippines, Luzon (genital slide 20018, in MWM). 9. Juxta and anellus of Polyphena chongzuoensis sp. nov., holotype. 10. Tip of aedeagus of P. chongzuoensis sp. nov., holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3385537/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="435">6</figureCitation>
) are resembling each other in appearance, but the former has a much more reduced, small triangle greenish patch, the latter has a larger greenish patch reaching the costa of forewing. In male genitalia, the new species can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cai" baseAuthorityYear="1983" box="[213,296,1598,1624]" class="Insecta" family="Limacodidae" genus="Polyphena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="435" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bana">
<emphasis box="[213,296,1598,1624]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="435">P. bana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the shorter spurs of anellus and aedeagus with distinctly smaller apical process (
<figureCitation box="[1234,1357,1598,1625]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1919,1944]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,191,1879]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,174,1879]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–10. Male genitalia. 5. Polyphena herbifera, Nepal (genital slide 11211, in MWM). 6. P. bana, China, Guangdong (in SCAU). 7. P. chongzuoensis sp. nov., holotype. 8. Parasa semperi, Philippines, Luzon (genital slide 20018, in MWM). 9. Juxta and anellus of Polyphena chongzuoensis sp. nov., holotype. 10. Tip of aedeagus of P. chongzuoensis sp. nov., holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3385537/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="435">Figs. 9, 10</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1418,2021]" pageId="1" pageNumber="435">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1634,1661]" pageId="1" pageNumber="435">Description.</emphasis>
Male adult (
<figureCitation box="[496,577,1634,1661]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1279,1304]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,301,1260]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,301,1260]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Adults.1. Polyphena herbifera, Nepal (in MWM).2. P. bana, China Guangdong (in SCAU). 3. P.chongzuoensis sp. nov., holotype. 4. Parasa semperi, holotype (in NHM). Scale bar =10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3385535/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="435">Figs. 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[593,622,1635,1661]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1987,2012]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,166,1955]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,166,1955]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 11. Venation of Polyphena chongzuoensis sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3385539/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="435">11</figureCitation>
). Length of forewing 
<quantity box="[880,978,1635,1661]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="435" unit="mm" value="7.5" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="7.0">7–8 mm</quantity>
. Head brown, vertex with dense scales. Antennae brown, broadly bipectinate basally, filiform distally. Labial palpus upturned, scattered with yellow scales. Haustellum absent. Thorax green dorsally, with brown dorsal fascia in the middle. Forewing ground color brown, with a small green patch with fuzzy margins at the basal area; vein Sc relatively straight, R1 and R2 almost parallel, R3+4 branching from near the base of R5, with R3 extending to apex, M1 parallel to M2, M2 and M3 separated basally. Hindwing blackish brown; Rs and M1 stalked basally, M2 and M3 almost parallel. The tibial spurs formula is 0-2-2. Abdomen dark brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1418,2021]" pageId="1" pageNumber="435">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[373,521,1886,1913]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1919,1944]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,191,1879]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,174,1879]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–10. Male genitalia. 5. Polyphena herbifera, Nepal (genital slide 11211, in MWM). 6. P. bana, China, Guangdong (in SCAU). 7. P. chongzuoensis sp. nov., holotype. 8. Parasa semperi, Philippines, Luzon (genital slide 20018, in MWM). 9. Juxta and anellus of Polyphena chongzuoensis sp. nov., holotype. 10. Tip of aedeagus of P. chongzuoensis sp. nov., holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3385537/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="435">Figs. 7, 9, 10</figureCitation>
). Uncus claw-shaped, strongly sclerotized apically, broaden basally. Gnathos slen- der, stick-like laterally. Valvae long triangle-shaped, narrowing from base to apex. Saccus short, U-shaped. Juxta flattened, medially with a dorsal round incision. Anellus with two rows of spines dorsally. Aedeagus long, tubeshaped, with slightly developed apical process.
</paragraph>
